Question:
According to the figure, which of the following statements about oriented links is correct?

Options:
A: Reversing the orientation of all components gives an equivalent oriented link
B: Reversing the orientation of only one component necessarily yields an equivalent link
C: Every link has exactly one orientation
D: Oriented link diagrams are in one-to-one correspondence with oriented links in \(S^3\)
E: \\

message.content:
Reversing the orientation of every component of an oriented link gives an equivalent oriented link; reversing only one component can change the oriented-link type. Also, a given (unoriented) link can be oriented in multiple ways, and planar diagrams are not in literal one-to-one correspondence with links (they’re equivalent up to Reidemeister moves and isotopy, not uniquely).  

Answer:A
